@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@{u}So tell me what this KewlCDPro thing is?@{uu}

   This is a kewl CD-ROM reader door (hence KewlCD!), with support for over a
year (or rather constant nagging) KewlCD has got to a stage I never intended it
to be at! In it's most basic form, it allows users to look through files on the
CD-ROM and let them download whatever they like, but in its current form its
almost an entire filebase of its own! You can even "download" files from the CD
from a local login, and have them copied to the directory of your choice :o).

   As of 2.0 it turned shareware, this is due to the amount of time &
effort I am putting into these doors. When money's involved i'm sure you will
agree also that you get less bugs and a higher quality product. I'm not asking
alot for full access to this and many other doors by me, please click @{" here " LINK registration}
for more information. Registering also allows you to use a program called
@{b}DirScanner@{ub} which will AUTOMATICALLY create .kewlcdpro (CD Config) files
for KewlCDPro!

   There are so many features now you may as well just try out the door for
yourself to see how powerful it is, so I won't list any.

@{u}Requirements@{uu}
 
o Kickstart 1.3+ for main door.
o Kickstart 2.0+ for KewlCD-Copy&Update, `View-only' (Flashfind) search and
  KewlCDPro Config Editor.
o MAX's BBS V1.54 68000 (NOT 68030 edition) or MAX's Pro.
o A CD-ROM with at least one CD :o).
o A fair amount of memory is used while the door is in use.

(P.S. This doesn't work with FTP-Mount, I tried it :o(..)

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Install" "Press Ctrl+Left Amiga+Right Amiga+A to continue"
@{u}How to Install KewlCD@{uu}

   Copy all of this to @{b}Doors:@{ub}, you're probably reading this from where you 
extract your archives to, so there should be a directory in @{b}Doors:@{ub} now called
@{b}KewlCD and there should be all these files in it. @{b}Doors:KewlCD/@{ub} should exist :)

   Now let's look inside of it, you will see a few directories, firstly let's
look at @{b}Flashfind 1.2@{ub}. Copy the file @{b}FlashFind@{ub} from the @{b}Flashfind 1.2@{ub}
directory to C:. Eg.

Copy "Doors:KewlCD/Flashfind 1.2/Flashfind" to C:

Now you've done that you can delete the entire @{b}Flashfind 1.2@{ub} directory, you
can read the documentation to Flashfind if you like but its not important as
Flashfind is used by KewlCD to do it's fast searches. Now also notice a
directory called @{b}RunBack@{ub}, in this directory there is only one file,
@{b}RunBack@{ub}, copy this to C: as well, this is used for the prefetch cache when
downloading.

   Now have a look in the @{b}CDConfigs@{ub} directory, you will see some files which
have the extension of @{b}.kewlcdpro@{ub} these are the CD Configuration files which
we will refer to as the "CD Configs" from now on (it's easier to type!), these
are files which KewlCD uses to "know how to" access each CD and to know what 
directories to use, what sections there are and where the index files can be
found (and some other stuff) more on that later. The files in @{b}CDConfigs@{ub} are
pre-made straight for use with KewlCD with the appropriate CD-ROM, ie.
@{b}Aminet12.cfg@{ub} would be used with the Aminet12 CD for example :).

   CD Config files for KewlCDPro can and should end in @{b}.kewlcdpro@{ub}, older files,
ie. those used in CDROMDOOR or KewlCD will have an ending of @{b}.cfg@{ub}, I changed
this so it was easy to tell the difference between which CD Config files are
for which program. If you make any CD Configs for KewlCDPro please make the
filename end in @{b}.kewlcdpro@{ub} (ie. @{b}Aminet12.kewlcdpro@{ub}) and don't forget to update
any CD Configs which arn't specially for KewlCDPro otherwise they won't work!
  
   Now stick it in a menu, you might want your CD Rom for people who pay so set
the access levels accordingly, your menu should look sommat like this:
@{b}
Key  Function  Extra  LoAcc  HiAcc  Misc
C      34        0      5    10000  Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD [DRIVE:]
@{ub}
   The DRIVE: argument can be specified if you have more than one CD drive, if
you enter a DRIVE: (ie. CD0:) it will specifically use that drive and no others,
@{b}Please note:@{ub} this is only needed if you which to use the `Mode 1' method which
will be covered in the next section @{" How to make a KewlCD.cfg " LINK "Conf"}.

@{i}You should not use the DRIVE: argument if you use Mode 2 or only have one
drive. @{ui}

(BTW, the DRIVE: argument doesn't work with PARNET or SERNET so don't even try
it, it's already been tested :)...)

Once thats done, it's installed into the BBS, but it's not quite ready for use
yet...

@{i}@{b}Now, let's go to the @{" Configuration files section! " LINK Conf}@{ub}@{ui}

@ENDNODE


@NODE conf "Configuration"
@{u}Configuration - How to make a KewlCD.cfg@{uu}

(For people upgrading: Re-read this section, it includes information on the new
access levels for each CD-ROM feature and the new structure of the @{b}KewlCD.cfg@{ub}.)

   You must edit the list of CD Configs to use, this is in the file is
@{b}Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD.cfg@{ub} - this section will tell you what needs to be in it...

@{b}Line 1 - X,Y coordinates of the section name on the screen@{ub}

This is in the format of X,Y in which the X is the column and Y is the row at
which you want the section name to be displayed at, if you are using the
default ANSI with KewlCD this should be "26,4" (excluding the quotes, it is on
all of the examples, just enter the text inside the "".).

@{b}Line 2 - X,Y coordinates of section number on the screen@{ub}

This is in the format of X,Y in which the X is the column and Y is the row at
which you want the section NUMBER to be displayed at, if you are using the
default ANSI with KewlCD this should be "75,4".

@{b}Line 3 - X,Y coordinates of keypress prompt on the screen@{ub}

This is in the format of X,Y in which the X is the column and Y is the row at
which you want the keypress prompt to be at (the cursor), if you are using the
default ANSI with KewlCD this should be "16,23".

@{b}Line 4 - X,Y coordinates of the CD's name on the screen@{ub}
*New for 2.0*

This is in the format of X,Y in which the X is the column and Y is the row at
which you want the CD's name to be displayed, the default for this is "27,1".

@{b}Line 5 - Directory for "downloads" if local log-in@{ub}

This feature allows you to copy files from the CD-ROM to a directory on your
hard disk if its a local login allowing you to surf your CDs and get files
just as easy as your callers! The directory should be a common download
directory and if it IS a directory (and not an assign or device) it MUST
have a trailing slash. Example: "Comms:Downloads/".

@{b}Line 6 - Temporary directory to hold downloads@{ub}

This feature is optional, if you wish to disable it, just leave a BLANK LINE
here, this feature copies the file to be downloaded to an area on your hard 
disk beforehand, it also removes spaces from filenames in the process so it 
might be useful if you have an awkward CD, set this to a directory with at
least 4meg free, users will not be able to download the file if it exceeds
the storage space on the hard disk. This feature also uses a pre-fetch cache
as of 2.0 which allows the next file to be copied as the current is
downloading. Again this must have a trailing slash if it is a directory.
Example: "BBS:Files/Temporary/".

@{b}Line 7 - Your name (Sysop's name)@{ub}
*New for 2.0*

On this line you must enter your name (the Sysop's name), this is used for the
Request CD feature and allows users to tells you what CD they want (whether it
be in your collection or not).
Example: "Joe Bloggs".

@{b}Line 8 - Maximum number of marked files@{ub}
*New for 2.0*

This is a number, it can be any number between 0 and possibly 99999+, it sets
the maximum number of files a user is allowed to mark in one go.
Example: "30".

@{b}Line 9 - Dual column list display for Mode 2 on/off@{ub}
*New for 2.0*

If you do not yet know about the CD modes then you will find out in a few
lines time :), this little line tells KewlCDPro to use a dual column list for
"Mode 2" allowing twice the number of CDs to fit on the screen (but limiting
the CD's name to about 38 characters). If you have a lot of CDs it might be
a good idea to enable this. This has no effect if mode 1 is used.
Enter a "0" for OFF (disable) or a "1" for ON (enable), nothing else!

@{b}Line 10 - Allow compressed downloads (archiving of lists/results)@{ub}
*New for 2.0*

See the @{" Compressed Downloads " LINK compress} section for more info on this, but this
line enables the archive menu to be displayed before downloading index files
and ASCII results. Archiving text files usualy has a great affect and can
reduce download times in half sometimes (although the user can still select
an un-compressed download!).
Enter a "0" for OFF (disable) or a "1" for ON (enable), nothing else!

@{b}Line 11 - CD mode for handling CDs@{ub}

This is a number, either 1 or 2, here is an explanation of what the numbers do:

@{b}1 -@{ub} This will create a menu showing a list of the CDs that are available to the
    user, it will check each entry in the list to see which one is in the drive
    and tell the user what CD it found, if it found none then it will bring up
    a little message and quit, also it will not display any CDs that the user
    does not have access levels high enough to see.
    
    If you want to use this feature with 2 CD-Drives (with any more or a
    multi CD-changer it would be worth using 'mode 2'), you can have two
    options in say a "CD-ROM" accessing menu, and under each entry in the menu
    you specify the DEVICE as an argument when running the door, e.g.
    Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD CD0: - this will check which CD is in CD0: and then
    look at the list of CDs and see which one it is, note you don't need the
    device argument if you only have 1 CD drive. You could have a menu like:
    
    @{b}Key:  Function:  Extra:  Lo acc:  Hi acc:  Filename/Etc:@{ub}
    1     34         0       5        10000    Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD CD0:
    2     34         0       5        10000    Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD CD1:

    Remember: 3 or more CD drives or a CD-Changer and you should use 'mode 2'
    instead and you don't need to specify the DEVICE argument if you only have
    one drive, hey, you can even use 'mode 2' for 2 drives, its just a matter
    of preference!

@{b}2 -@{ub} This will create a list as before, showing the CDs, this is meant for
    users of multiple CD drives or CD-Changers, it will give a prompt at the
    bottom and ask a user to enter the CD to access, if its not in a drive it
    will tell them that and to select another. If you enabled Dual column list
    display (a few lines up), this will be displayed in 2 columns allowing
    twice the number of CDs to be displayed. @{i}Registered users only! @{ui}
    OUT CD's are displayed in red and don't have the number next to them, IN
    CD's are displayed in yellow.

@{b}The rest of the lines...@{ub}

You now make a list of the CDs you have available, each CD has two lines of
information for it:

The first line should be the full path and file to the CD Config, and the
second line should be the minimum access level required to access the CD-ROM.

Once you have completed the list, it MUST be terminated with a hash (#).. See
the supplied example @{b}KewlCD.cfg@{ub} for info.. The finished @{b}KewlCD.cfg@{ub} will end up
looking something like:

26,4                                                 << Coords for section name
75,4                                               << Coords for section number
16,20                                             << Coords for keypress prompt
27,1                                                      << Coords for CD name
Comms:Downloads/                     << Directory for downloads on local log-in
                           << Temporary directory for downloads (disabled here)
Joe Bloggs                                                 << Your Name (SysOp)
30                                            << Maximum number of marked files
1                                            << Dual column list display on/off
0                                                        << Archive menu on/off
1                                                          << Mode of operation
Doors:KewlCD/CDConfigs/Aminet16.kewlcdpro              << Filename of CD config
5                                                      << Access level for this
Doors:KewlCD/CDConfigs/Aminet17.kewlcdpro                             << Etc...
10
Doors:KewlCD/CDConfigs/SharewareStudio9.kewlcdpro
2
Doors:KewlCD/CDconfigs/Euroscene1.kewlcdpro
5
Doors:KewlCD/CDconfiga/Pornworld.kewlcdpro                            << <grin>
100                                            << Don't want normal peeps here!
#                                         << Never delete this terminating hash
^- Don't remove that sexy hash!                  

(example configuration file included in archive named @{b}KewlCD.cfg.example@{ub})

@{u}The Menu Keys@{uu}

As of 2.0, you can now alter the menu keys so you can design your own menu.
Click @{" here " LINK keyboard} for more information!

@{u}ANSIs@{uu}

All the screens can be edited and changed to your liking, the @{b}CPSAnsi.text@{ub},
@{b}CPSAnsiBF.text@{ub}, @{b}Ratio.text@{ub}, @{b}RatioBF.text@{ub} and @{b}CPSFont.text@{ub} screens are
EXACTLY the same as used in MagicFile. Which means any font or ansi screen for
MagicFile's BIG CPS or Ratio display can be used with KewlCDPro too!

@{u}Notes@{uu}

Note: CD configs are ending in @{b}.kewlcdpro@{ub} because they are specifically for
KewlCDPro and won't work with anything else, if the files end in @{b}.cfg@{ub} they will
be for KewlCD or CDROMDOOR (yuck) and will need to be updated for use with 
KewlCDPro, see the @{" Making or updating a CD Config file " LINK "cd.cfg"} section.

READ ON...

@{" Using Parnet or Sernet with KewlCDPro " LINK parnet}

@{" Making or updating a CD Config file " LINK cd.cfg}

@{" Compressed downloads " LINK compress}

@{" How to make index and config files for CDs with no index files! " LINK noindex}

@{" Save making .kewlcdpro files, register and get DirScanner! " LINK registration}

@ENDNODE


@NODE localdownloads "Local Downloads"
@{u}Local Downloads@{uu}

   This is a useful little feature, this allows you to copy files from CD's to
your hard disk. Known as local downloading, at first this must seem pretty
pointless but it's actually quite useful. It's for registered users only.

   Firstly, you must have set up KewlCDPro and have a CD in the drive (with
related CD Config) to use this feature.

   You use KewlCDPro as any normal user would accessing your BBS, you can list
sections, search for files, mark files and everything else. This means even if
the file is lost in the depths of directories, you can find it easily with
KewlCDPro.

   To local download, mark all the files you wish to download from the CD, then
press the download key on the main menu (usualy D). A file requester will pop
up with your default directory (specified in the @{" configuration " LINK conf}), or in `Sys:' if
one hasn't been specified. Choose the directory you want the files to go in to,
or leave it as the default one, and then click @{b}OK@{ub} to copy the files to your
hard disk or @{b}Cancel@{ub} to not to.

   That's it really, help for any other KewlCDPro functions can be obtained by
pressing the help key (usualy H) on the menu.

@ENDNODE


@NODE keyboard "The KewlCDPro Keyboard"
@{u}The KewlCDPro Keyboard@{uu}

   If you are a registered user of LSD Doors or the Other-reg Keyfile, you can
use the KewlCDPro Config Editor which makes life a LOT easier for you! Extra
docs are included for the Config Editor, but it's pretty straight forward, but
you need to go into the Keyboard ED section from the menu to edit the menu
keys. If you want to disable a menu function set the key as a dash (-) and you
won't be able to access that function. Don't forget to change the Main menu
ANSI's to reflect the key presses.

@{u}The Keyboard.cfg@{uu}

   If you haven't got access to the KewlCDPro Config Editor, here is what you
have to do instead. Edit the file @{b}Keyboard.cfg@{ub} and you see a list of letters,
each one of these letters represents a key press, below is a list of what each
key press is.

@{u}Key Function Name@{uu}   @{u}Description of Key@{uu}       @{u}Default key@{uu}

KEY_LIST          - Listing files            [L]
KEY_DOWNLOAD      - Download file(s)         [D]
KEY_FIND          - File finder              [F]
KEY_HELP          - Help section             [H]
KEY_QUIT          - Quit KewlCDPro           [Q]
KEY_EDITMARKED    - Edit marked files list   [E]
KEY_CLEARMARKED   - Clear all marked files   [C]
KEY_REQUEST       - Request a CD             [R]
KEY_SECINDEX      - Download current index   [G]
KEY_INDEX         - Download global index    [T]
KEY_PREVSEC       - Previous section         [P]
KEY_SELSEC        - Section select list      [S]
KEY_NEXTSEC       - Next section             [N]

   There we go, you need all these keys present in the Keyboard.cfg for it to
work in KewlCDPro. Remeber: Enter a dash (-) to disable a function!

@ENDNODE


@NODE Parnet "Using Parnet or Sernet with KewlCD"
@{u}For those that use Parnet or Sernet to access their CDs@{uu}

   Before you could only safely allow people to freely use the network if you
*knew* the other computer was always on and connected up, well heres a pretty
safe way of leaving the door with no need to enable or disable the door itself
and you decide if the CD is on or not by simply turning the CD on or off and 
activating the network, here's how:

   Assign all the disks in your assign list at startup, but make sure you set 
them all as 'LATE' or 'DEFER'... Ie...

(Standard AmigaDOS)
Assign Aminet_0794: Net:Aminet_0794 DEFER

(Assplus)
Aminet_0794: Net:Aminet_0794 D

(@{" MCP " LINK "MCP"} assign lists)
Aminet_0794: Net:Aminet_0794    (and have LATE selected for the entry)

   Do this for all your CDs and then set that up in each CD Config, my door 
will only check ACTIVE (ie. the LATE or DEFER has been cancelled out and the
assign can be used normally, this is done by simply accessing the assign, like
"Dir Aminet_0794: >nil:").

   Please note: You CANNOT specify the [DRIVE:] argument for 'Mode 1' because I
directly ask the OS what disk in in the drive you specify, OK so you COULD put
NET:CD0 (haven't seen if this works or not) but from what I have done it seems
it will not work because I ask for the volume name of "NET:CD0" which
consequently would get the volume name from NET: (because in sernet and parnet,
each device is indicated by a DRAWER and drawers do not have volume names 
because they are not volumes, (they have drawer names instead :).).).

   If you want to change a CD over in your drive, DON'T FORGET to REMOVE the
assign!! E.g. Assign Aminet_0794: REMOVE - and you will hafta reassign it if
you want to use that one again, complex but the only way you can use a network
CD carefully, also if you turn off the network CD after KewlCDPro has been used
you will either hafta remove all the used assigns or reset the BBS machine.

   This is a *safe* way of using the network, because usualy if the network 
isn't connected properly, it will lock your computer for ages until either you
connect up the network or it time-outs and the 'no disk present' requester
comes up, but this will avoid this problem and so your BBS won't lock up! 

@{u}Warning for PARNET users!@{uu}

   This @{b}WILL@{ub} make those darn annoying "Act 2.0pkt whatever" requesters
come up, you will need to use either MCP's REQUESTER TIMEOUT function or get
NetPatch (also availible from my @{" BBS " LINK "BBS"}) which will patch these errors out and
fix a few other bugs in ParNET too. 

   If you run Kickstart 2.0+ on your client you may switch to ProNET which is a
fully featured Parallel and Serial networking package, more powerful and faster
than ParNET or SerNET and uses ParNET + null modem cables!

@ENDNODE


@NODE cd.cfg "How to make or update a CD Configuration file"
@{u}How to make or update a CD Config file@{uu}
 
   All CD Configs should be placed in the @{b}Doors:KewlCD/CDconfigs/@{ub} directory,
please also don't confuse the @{b}KewlCD.cfg@{ub} file (which must be located at 
@{b}Doors:KewlCD/KewlCD.cfg@{ub}) with the CD Configs as the @{b}KewlCD.cfg@{ub} contains a list
of CD Configs to use and more. 

   CD Configs created specifically for KewlCDPro *SHOULD* end in @{b}.kewlcdpro@{ub}
so that they can be told apart from the older CD Configs (which end in @{b}.cfg@{ub},
these can be updated by changing the first 5 or so lines, see below!).

@{u}If you are making an Aminet CD or Shareware Studio Config read here@{uu}

   A program called @{b}DirScanner@{ub} is available when you register LSD Doors,
written by me it allows you to create @{b}.kewlcdpro@{ub} (CD Config) files for
KewlCDPro. It will automatically create for both Aminet and Shareware studio
CDs, AND also unknown CDs or CDs without index files (in which case it makes
the index files too!!). Don't delay, @{" register today " LINK registration}, save all that manual
labour!

@{u}If you are updating/checking a config for compatiblity for KewlCDPro@{uu}
 
   A support program called KewlCD-Copy&Update has been included which will
update any config from KewlCD (or KewlCDProBETA) to KewlCDPro, it will fill in
lines 4 & 5 automaticly if it regonizes the CD and it will check if the paths +
index files are valid in the config (to stop typing errors). Read the supplied
docs with it to find out more!

@{u}What a CD Config file consists of...@{uu}

   If you are making a new config for a CD then firstly load up your fave text
editor and start to make the file. If you are updating a CD go through the
list below and make absolutly sure everything is OK to be used with this 
version of KewlCDPro. You will need to update the config if it has come from
the CDROMDOOR V2.1+ or KewlCD (non-pro versions) and KewlCDProBETA...

@{b}Line 1: Volume Name of CD-ROM@{ub}
   
Must be the volume name of the CD ROM, used for identification. For example 
Aminet12: for the Aminet 12 CD.

@{b}Line 2: Name of Current Disk@{ub}

Used to tell the user what CD has been chosen at the beginning. You could write
"Aminet 12 for Amiga software" for Aminet12.

@{b}Line 3: Short Disk Identity@{ub}

Used as a marked files disk identity because I found a bug that DOS can only 
handle so many chars so people with big names and big CD-ROM titles were
getting too big for the DOS. The solution is to use this line as a SHORT DISK 
ID. For example, A12 for Aminet 12 or SS5 for Shareware Studio 5, giving marked
files names like @{b}Joe Bloggs.SS5@{ub}.

Caution: If anything is in here it will be used for the short disk ID (even if 
it is long) so if anyones written any credits or comments in this line please
remove it before use. Use line 7 for credits if you *HAVE* to :)).

@{b}Line 4: Listing field position data@{ub}

Position-FileSize,Position-FileDescript

NOTE: The comma (,) must separate the two, so please include it!

In the PRO version of KewlCD you can now have cursor key marking, now this
marking system is OK but data must be stored somewhere about the CD, and well
all this does is reads the index file (see line below for info on what it reads)
and prints stuff on the screen/holds it for future use, the size and file
description field positions depend on the longest file length and the biggest
size.

The two settings on this line are used to set the starting position of the
file size and file description fields on the screen. The reason I did this
is because the further the fields are apart, the smaller the comment can be, so
if you try to squash the longest size possible from the CD next to the longest 
filename there should be at the most 1 character space, it doesn't really matter
if say one file happens to touch, thats one file in several thousand. Play 
around with these values to get them optimised, look at the very bottom of this
section for a table of values to use for certain CDs. Note that the size field
is right-justified so that it looks nice.

Here are some that have already been worked out for you:

Aminet 1-5         20,29
Aminet 6+          19,28
Shareware Studio   13,22

Don't forget to enter the values *exactly* including the comma!

@{b}Line 5: Index data@{ub}

Start-Name,End-Name,Start-Size,End-Size,Start-Descript,End-Descript,Ignore

It may look a bit confusing, but i'll explain each one so don't worry...

NOTE: The commas (,) must separate all of them, so please include them!

This is the line that tells KewlCDPro what bits it needs to read from the index
file to get the information about filenames and stuff...

Start-Name and End-Name are the starting and ending positions of the filename
field in the index file, Start-Name will usualy be 1 because it is the first
field on the line on most index files, End-Name is 19 for recent Aminet CDs,
20 for the older Aminets (before Aminet 6), 12 for MS-DOS ISO9660 style CDs
and around 30 for full filenames (but I haven't seen any with this many!).

Start-Size and End-Size are the starting and ending positions of the filesize
field in the index file, there is no standard for these positions, I have
made a table below this to help though.

Start-Descript and End-Descript are the starting and ending positions of the
file description field - this one is as important as the other two, because it
lets the users know what they are downloading before they actually do it! I
have put in an "Easy life" option here, just enter -1 for the End-Descript and
KewlCDPro will automaticly grab the description till the end of the line, this
can be used for most index files.

Ignore is the number of lines to ignore at the start of each index file, this is
useful for the Aminet CDs because they have a 2 line header at the start of each
index file, so you would enter 2 for Aminet, check if the CD you are using has
headers, count of the number of lines it takes up and enter it in here, if the
index files do not have any headers then simply put a 0 here.

Here are some that have already been worked out for you:

Aminet 1-5         1,20,32,36,38,-1,2
Aminet 6+          1,19,31,34,40,-1,2
Shareware Studio   1,12,13,21,34,-1,0

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Counting the positions is often quite tricky to get exact and it is important
that it IS exact otherwise you can cause nasty problems. You can use any text
editor or ansi editor for that matter to do it, well any that have a counter
on them which tells you what column the cursor is currently in, make sure the
first character on the line is at column 1 though and not 0, if it is at 0 then
increase each of the numbers you put into the CD Config by one.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------         

@{b}Line 6: Full path and name of the main INDEX file for that CD@{ub}

If there isn't one then leave a BLANK LINE, this is only for download purposes
and also the 'view-only' file finding search feature. For example, 
Aminet12:Aminet/INDEX for Aminet 12.

@{b}Line 7: Author of CD Config, ie. copyright information etc.@{ub}

@{b}Line 8: Number of sections on Current Disk@{ub}

Most CD-ROMS are conveniently divided into 'sections' - this value represents 
the number of `sections' (usually in dirs) on this disk.

@{b}Line 9: <Section Name>  <Path to listing file>   <Path to section>@{ub}

Repeat for number of times needed (the value in line 8). You must make an entry
for each 'section', 1 line each, with section name, a path & and name to a text
listing of the files in that section (only used for downloading purposes), and 
a path to that section. Each of the lines MUST be in quotes.. no commas are 
needed to separate the strings, just like this :

         "Name"   "Listing File"   "Path"

         No quotes needed for first 8 lines of the config.. 
         It is probably a good idea to make the Section Name in the format that
         was needed for earlier versions of KewlCD with the lame (tho fast)
         searches. I entitled this 'NEWLOOK' <G>, this consists of several
         major changes to ya ordinary section name :). Please read the section
         in {~ File Finding Facility " LINK "xtra" 42} about NEWLOOK.

   Save it to the @{b}Doors:KewlCD/CDconfigs@{ub} directory under an appropriate name &
add it to your @{b}KewlCD.cfg@{ub}! Ta-da! Don't forget to test all the sections and 
stuff, you don't want to be running a dodgy config :).

Read the docs supplied with KewlCD-Copy&Update to find out what that clever &
handy little prog does!

Remeber, make life easier by using DirScanner, @{" register today " LINK registration}!

@ENDNODE


@NODE compress "Compressed Downloads"
@{u}Compressed Downloads@{uu}

   This is a nice little addition to 2.0 and allows index files/ASCII results
to be compressed before downloading. To enable this feature check out the
@{" Configuration section " LINK conf} or use KewlCDConfigED to enable it (registered users
only).

   A menu, @{b}Compress.text@{ub}, is displayed before any transfer takes place allowing
the user to select which archiver they want (or non-compressed). The menu
should reflect the archiver configuration file @{b}Compress.cfg@{ub}, plus the
extra option added automatically by KewlCD Pro for non-compressed downloads.

   Once the user has chosen the format they want, the file will be compressed
(if need be) and then sent to the user, afterwards it will delete the tempory
file.

@{u}Compress.cfg@{uu}

   Each line of the configuration file is for an archiver, the file that comes
with KewlCD Pro has the three most common archivers already set-up; LHA, LZX
and ZIP. Each line of the configuration file should contain:

archiver extension,command line to execute the archiver

e.g.

.lha,LHA -q a

(Comma required! The -q supresses all output from LHA.)

   The end of the file should have a blank line or # (hash) just to be on the
safe side, although a blank line will do. E.g.

.lha,LHA -q a
.lzx,LZX -q a
.zip,ZIP -q
#

@ENDNODE


@NODE xtra "File Finding Facility"
@{u}File Finding@{uu}

   As of the Pro versions, there is now a subtle cursor key marking implemented,
this allows easy marking & unmarking of files, there is a global markable search
but it aint very fast which is a bit of a shame, I will optimise it as it goes
on tho and so i've kept FlashFind search which is now known as a `view-only'
fast search :)..

@{u}What Flashfind is@{uu}

   I use an external program called FlashFind which will do all the searching
dirty work for me, it will search the index files and find out what matches and
show the entire line to the user, no matter what matches it will be shown
(unfortuantly this also means the filesize and directory in the case of the
Aminet CDs but that could be a feature in a way), it shows the entire line. Its
VERY fast BTW (fastest search routine Dave has seen too!)!! This was originally
the only search method but after I implemented the cursor key marking, it has 
been seen as an extra.

@{u}Searching new life and new civilizations (not ECS version)@{uu}
 
   Search is split up into 2 main modes, Current section and GLOBAL, the first
will only search the current section's index file for any matchings and will
give the option to mark any of them (if any) and thats about it, but theres the
GLOBAL search....

   This search is split up into 2 main modes, there is the MARKABLE search and 
the 'view-only' search. The 'view-only' search uses an external program as said
before, it is extremely fast (faster than the dopus searcher etc) but it won't
allow u to mark files because there is no info to what or where the file is so
it's just a view search for now. It uses the CD's main index file (if its not
availible then it doesn't work) and it searches thru the file and will print
anything it finds to match, it would be useful here if the user knows which
section the file is in, so in example of the Aminet CDs it shows the directory 
after the filename @{i}WHICH IS GOOD! @{ui}@{b}BUT...@{ub} The section name must
have something along the theme of the real directory name.. Let me give you a 
little story to explain this (please note: this isn't really needed for the new
version because the flashfind search isn't NEEDED anymore but is still there 
just for the sake..)

A user wants to find MCP in a global search, so he does this and it gets the
results (for example on an aminet cd).

MCP132b12.lha    wb/util  334k+A kewl Workbench enhancer program, best around!
MCPmoni.lha      wb/moni   60k+Monitors for WB.
Shitheads.lha    no/way    20k+New game from the McPye brothers!

(maybe not that last one)

Anyway the user thinks "WOW! I always wanted MCP132b5.lha!! And it's in wb/util!"
now, how does he know what the hell that section is?? I'm sure you get the
picture...

Workbench - Utilities  ...now that suggests wb/util - or you could do...
Workbench utils (wb/util)  ... that is probably your best bet- so create your
configs from scratch in this NEWLOOK way because it looks much nicer!

   Anyway, once the user has done the search it displays the list, prompts a
return and then goes back to the main kewlcd menu...

@{u}To bodly go where no bold man has boldly gone before...@{uu}
 
   The other option is the markable search which can be aborted at any time BTW,
it is about 50x slower than flashfind but very easy to use, it also looks nice &
well you can mark files with the cursor keys, it is transparent to the user but
this has a lot of work going on internally, also it uses up no extra ram so the
search is a little compromised. I could load in each index into ram, then search
that but a) It would be too much hassle and would waste memory and b) I don't 
know I could pull it off without a lot of (wasted) effort.

@ENDNODE


@NODE Registration "Registering LSD Doors"
@{u}Registration@{uu}

   This version of KewlCDPro contains special features which can only be
unlocked if the LSD Doors or the LSD OtherReg keyfile is purchased. The LSD
Doors keyfile also unlocks many support programs by LSD and many future works.

   To register please see the file `-RegForm-' contained in the this archive,
